"GSA Justification: This contract is not for consulting services, as it provides staff augmentation support to complete strategic planning deliverables required by the GPRA Modernization Act of 2010 and directly execute the agency’s strategic planning responsibilities.  Background:  •	The Task Order’s Performance Work Statement explains that the contract support would carry out EXIM’s strategic planning requirements, as outlined in OMB Circular A-11, Part 6.  •	These responsibilities include assisting creating a FY 2025 workplan for EXIM’s strategic planning, coordinating internal stakeholders for the drafting of a new strategic plan, and assisting with annual and quarterly metrics related to EXIM’s Strategic Plan. •	The contractor supports the drafting of legally required reporting under the GPRA Modernization Act of 2010, including EXIM’s Annual Performance Plan and Annual Performance Report."

" Background: •	This contract provides a temporary staff augmentation solution to support budget operations, with contractors directly involved in the execution of budget-related tasks. •	They contribute to accurate financial reporting and promote transparency in budget matters. •	They are responsible for preparing and distributing the January 2025 Division Budget Reports, ensuring timely and precise documentation. •	Additionally, the contractor is assisting staff in assessing the reestimate process, helps align the project schedule, and supports the analysis of workbooks, Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs), and other related documentation to ensure milestones and deliverables are met. •	The contractors perform stress test analysis on the portfolio, validate portfolio data, and prepare the loss reserve report, ensuring accurate and reliable financial assessments. •	They handle other data calls based on portfolio data, providing the necessary insights and documentation to support decision-making. •	The staff keeps abreast of executive orders and relevant OMB Circulars, including A-11 (which provides guidance on preparing, submitting, and executing the federal budget) and A-129 (which outlines the policies and procedures for managing and accounting for federal credit programs), ensuring all budgetary processes comply with the latest federal guidelines and mandates. •	The staff is knowledgeable of the Federal Credit Reform Act (FCRA) as it relates to the portfolio, ensuring compliance with FCRA provisions for budgeting, accounting, and reporting of federal credit programs."

"GSA Justification: This is not a contract for consulting services and these non-consulting services fulfill EXIM’s mission by ensuring compliance with OMB Circular No. A-123 and best practices, providing staff augmentation support and providing highly skilled analysts who serve as integral team members in executing critical internal controls functions across the agency.  Background: ·   Provides a staffing solution to support the internal controls program. - Conducts assessments and reviews to assess, monitor and evaluation of financial and non-financial internal controls in compliance with OMB Circular No. A-123. -Supports the integration of internal controls with enterprise risk management processes, in compliance with OMB Circular No. A-123. -Provides training to enhance capabilities across the agency."

The contract provides ongoing services in support of conducting improper payment risk assessments identifying risk susceptible programs coordination with OMB and other stakeholders regarding improvements to the improper payment methodologies. The contract is critical to FSA’s efforts to implement the requirements of the Payment Integrity Information Act of 2019 (PIIA) and A-123C.  Without it, FSA will not be compliant with this law.  This non-compliance will be reported in both the financial statement audit and in the separate mandatory annual PIIA compliance audit

The contract provides ongoing assessment of FSA internal controls in compliance with A-123A and other related relevant criteria; which includes providing services for internal controls planning and support documentation and design. This contract support is in accordance with the Chief Financial Officer (CFO) Act of 1990, which requires the Department of Education (Department) to prepare and submit annual audited financial statements to verify the accuracy of our financial reporting.  Further, in 20 U.S. Code § 1018, Federal Student Aid (FSA) is required to adhere to the CFO Act and undergo an annual independent financial audit.  The A-123A internal controls contract is critical to efforts to resolve the prior year financial statement disclaimer and material weakness.

description: The BFCC-SC shall administer surveys, collect customer service experience using surveys that target stakeholders engaged with the BFCC-QIOs or any other CMS quality improvement contractors. The BFCC-SC services are national in scope and cover contracted areas throughout the United States including territories. The BFCC-SC shall serve as a source of information for identifying gaps and achievements based on survey of satisfaction surveys to achieve CMS’ aims. The SC will serve as a driver of the CCSQ iQIIG strategic vision and goals assisting in the creation of widespread quality improvement in the QIO program supporting over 50 million Medicare beneficiaries. The BFCC-SC shall collaborate with BFCC-QIOs, advise CMS on opportunities for improving the program, and identify best practices for possible dissemination amongst the QIOs. Additionally, the BFCC-SC will contribute to the knowledgebase of QIO programs any best practices of what works well regarding providing direct assistance to Medicare beneficiaries.

description: The Beneficiary and Family Centered Care (BFCC) Audit and Interrater Reliability (AIRR) review contractor will conduct audits in specific BFCC-Quality Improvement Organization (BFCC-QIO) service areas to determine if the (BFCC-QIOs operations, programs or projects are functioning effectively and efficiently. These audits will include a review of a designated number of cases claims per contracted service area. The audits will use Inter-rater reliability reviews of Beneficiary Appeals and Short Stay claims to assess the validity and accuracy of the BFCC-QIOs reviews. The AIRR contractor will also systematically screen medical records for adverse patient safety events that occurred in hospitals and other settings using a standardized process and review each medical record that is positive for an adverse patient safety event to determine “the completeness, adequacy and quality of the care provided.”"
